COMMENT.comment_text: Functions in this file look at most 3 pixels (a,b,c) to predict the 4th (d). * They're positioned like this: * prev: c b * row: a d * The Sub filter predicts d=a, Avg d=(a+b)/2, and Paeth predicts d to be * whichever of a, b, or c is closest to p=a+b-c.

The Sub filter predicts each pixel as the previous pixel, a. * There is no pixel to the left of the first pixel. It's encoded directly. * That works with our main loop if we just say that left pixel was zero.

The Sub filter predicts each pixel as the previous pixel, a. * There is no pixel to the left of the first pixel. It's encoded directly. * That works with our main loop if we just say that left pixel was zero.

The Avg filter predicts each pixel as the (truncated) average of a and b. * There's no pixel to the left of the first pixel. Luckily, it's * predicted to be half of the pixel above it. So again, this works * perfectly with our loop if we make sure a starts at zero.

Paeth tries to predict pixel d using the pixel to the left of it, a, * and two pixels from the previous row, b and c: * prev: c b * row: a d * The Paeth function predicts d to be whichever of a, b, or c is nearest to * p=a+b-c. * * The first pixel has no left context, and so uses an Up filter, p = b. * This works naturally with our main loop's p = a+b-c if we force a and c * to zero. * Here we zero b and d, which become c and a respectively at the start of * the loop.
It's easiest to do this math (particularly, deal with pc) with 16-bit * intermediates.
Paeth breaks ties favoring a over b over c.
Note `_epi8`: we need addition to wrap modulo 255.
